“malaysia is majority islamic society still hard to accepted, even we still allowed to dressing as woman in public, we allowed to have speech, to working and earn money to survive, allowed to keep ours hair long and silk, we allowed to purchase estrogen hormone, doing both surgery. but at the end, we still need the equality laws to legally same sex-marriage, id/ passport to gender we wish to.” David Rose is a transgender woman from Malaysia, she now lives in Sweden. She left Malaysia, fearing for her life and seeking a place where she could live freely. “today, is my second years living in sweden, i feel love and be myself 100%. i found freedom and speech free or equality opportunity in organization”
// As part of #transweek, we are sharing stories of the transgender men and women who have lived through discrimination and continue to make their voices heard.
//
Read David Rose’s story shared with the #WhereLoveIsIllegal campaign, a platform for #LGBTI stories of #discrimination and #survival, at the link in our profile. At the link you can also see how to share your own experience of #discrimination and #survival and how you can support. #loveislove Photo provided by David Rose. This is a @witness_change project. For more stories of survival, follow @WhereLoveIsIllegal. #transisbeautiful

“I confessed myself as a homosexual for my family and for society. It was a very difficult time or stage of my life because it was a phase in which I was still in school.” Pepesta is a transgender woman from Mozambique. She came out to her family when she was 16 years old, which began discrimination she would continue to face in school and then in work. “I suffered a lot of bias at work because of my sexual orientation I have faced many challenges, and one of the worst challenges is access to health care services for being a trans woman.” This discrimination propelled Pepsta to becoming an activist, promoting access to healthcare for transgender people in Maputo.
//
